This paper deals with contextual word classification, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of kernel functions, which are commonly used in machine learning and optimization, indicating that cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper explores various strategies for improving performance, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The use of kernels for mapping data points into high dimensional spaces is also a common technique in neural networks, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses experiments on language modeling and machine translation tasks, which could also place it in the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category, as these tasks often involve image and text processing.
